Rodong Sinmun on S. Korea's "law-abiding oath system"
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, January 26 (KCNA) -- The chief executive of South Korea declared of late that the "law-abiding oath System" would be still enforced upon "political prisoners" including prisoners of conscience.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Commenting on this, Rodong Sinmun today says:   The "law-abiding oath system" is an "ideological conversion system" of new style, which forces the unconverted long-term prisoners, prisoners of conscience and other "political prisoners" to take an oath of "unconditionally abiding" by the "National Security Law" and other fascist laws.
   Nevertheless, the South Korean ruler openly expressed his intention to continue enforcing the evil system. This is a grave challenge and provocation to the pro-reunification and democratic forces calling for the repeal of the system.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Suppression of thought is a symptom of insanity of the tyrants whose remaining days are numbered. History shows that the political villains, who resort to physical and ideological suppression of people, go to their doom.
   The chief executive of South Korea must squarely look into the trend of the times and immediately abrogate the "NSL," "law-abiding oath system" and other fascist laws, as demanded by the people and unconditionally and promptly release unconverted long-term prisoners and all other arrested pro-reunification and pro-democracy patriots.
